english:
  title: Four Poems of Idle Fancy
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I
    Across the autumn waters, she appears—my beloved,
    Pines and cinnamon trees share a different nature;
    How can the heart find ease?
    I have a fine bolt of eastern silk,
    And wish to write my name upon it,
    That my longing might find some release.

    II
    The autumn moon hangs full and round,
    Autumn dew gathers and congeals.
    The Milky Way gleams pristine,
    And wind stirs with a whistling chill.
    My hemp coverlet lies thin and cold—
    Sleep will not come.
    From time to time a cricket strikes against the lamp.

    III
    A mountain hermit calls to me:
    "Return, come read my words."
    Bamboo shoots have grown into a forest now,
    Chestnuts hang heavy as fists.
    The courtyard fills with wind and rain,
    And moss grows thick and long.
    Autumn dew has dampened the qin's strings,
    And they hang slack and limp.

    IV
    Beside my pillow, time flies past like a bird.
    A hundred years of human life—
    How much, in truth, remains?
    Dreaming in the dust, rising to delusion—
    Whose fault is this?
    Bound by our own hands, bound by our own words,
    We become like silkworms, like moths—
    Caught in our own making.
  footnotes:
    - The 'eastern silk' (東絹) likely refers to Korean silk, valued as a precious commodity. The speaker wishes to declare his feelings through this fine material.
    - The 'mountain hermit' represents a reclusive figure, possibly the poet himself in another guise, inviting retreat from worldly concerns.
    - The qin (琴) is the traditional Chinese zither, here a symbol of refined sensibility dampened by the sorrows of autumn and time.
    - The final couplet employs Buddhist-influenced imagery of self-entrapment, comparing human self-delusion to the silk-spinning insect caught in its own creation.
